-- `mount_cell_volumes` / `umount_cell_volumes`
-- `setup_local_dev`
-- base writable links `/etc`, `/var`, `/tmp`, `/home`, `/root`, `/usr/pkg`, `/opt`
-  resolve through per-cell `/.overlay`
-
-Lifecycle actions:
-- `start_cell_internal`
-- `start_cell`, `stop_cell`, `restart_cell`
-- `stop_cell_processes`
-
-Prune paths:
-- `prune_runtime_cell`, `prune_runtime_all`
-- `prune_runtime_volume`, `prune_runtime_volumes`
-
-Backup paths:
-- volumes: `backup_volume`, `restore_volume`, `delete_volume_backup`
-- overlays: `backup_overlay`, `restore_overlay`, `delete_overlay_backup`
-
-
-6. Reconcile/apply internals
-----------------------------
-Entry points:
-- `run_reconcile_command`
-- `reconcile_all`
-- `reconcile_one_cell`
-- `reconcile_volumes`
-
-Dependency ordering:
-- `reconcile_order` performs topological ordering from `CELL_DEPENDS_ON`
-- missing dependency manifests and cycles are hard failures
-
-Cell-level state machine inputs:
-- manifest hash and prior `state/manifest.sha256`
-- apply hash and prior `state/apply.sha256`
-- runtime existence (`cell.conf` presence)
-- running state (`cell_exists`)
-- drift class:
-  - service drift (`autostart`, supervise cmd/log settings, depends, healthcheck, mounts)
-  - policy drift (`create profile`, reserved ports, rlimits)
-
-Notable reconcile behavior:
-- apply plan hash drift triggers `apply_cell_script`
-- autostarted running cell with apply drift is quiesced before plan run
-- policy-only drift warns unless `--restart-changed` is supplied
-- healthcheck runs post-convergence when configured and autostarted
-
-Return semantics:
-- per-cell reconcile returns `2` when changed, `0` when noop, non-zero on failure
-- global `apply --dry-run` returns `2` if any changes are pending
-
-
-7. Declarative plan parser internals
-------------------------------------
-Core parser:
-- `apply_declarative_plan`
-
-Execution helpers:
-- `apply_exec_in_cell`
-- `apply_write_block_file`
-- `apply_copy_host_file`
-- `apply_extract_host_tarball`
-- `apply_patch_block`
-
-Parser contracts:
-- uppercase directive enforcement
-- explicit block state machine for `FILE_BEGIN/FILE_END` and `PATCH_BEGIN/PATCH_END`
-- strict option parsing for `DIR`, `COPY`, `UNTAR`, `FILE_BEGIN`, `PATCH_BEGIN`
-- package token validation in `validate_pkg_name`
-- apply hash includes external host artifacts referenced by `COPY`/`UNTAR`
-
-Runtime notes:
-- `apply_cell_script` ensures cert store refresh via `certctl rehash`
-- stopped cells use `--ephemeral` path when applying with autostart `NO`
-
-
-8. IPC internals (`ipc serve --stdio`)
---------------------------------------
-Server path:
-- `run_ipc_resource_command`
-- `run_ipc_serve_command`
-- `ipc_serve_stdio`
-
-Protocol helpers:
-- `ipc_send_frame_file`
-- `ipc_read_payload`
-- `ipc_execute_call`
-
-Protocol constraints:
-- framed header format: `M 1 <TYPE> <ID> <P1> <P2> <P3> <LEN>`
-- payload hard limit: `67108864` bytes (64 MiB)
-- CALL mode `0` captures stdout/stderr, mode `1` binds command I/O to `/dev/tty`
-- optional single env override is validated (`[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*`)
-
-
-9. `cellui` integration internals
----------------------------------
-Bridge and protocol client:
-- `usr.sbin/cellui/adapter.c`
-
-Cell list parser contract:
-- command uses fixed `-o` field order with 18 columns
-- parser uses `split_tsv_fixed(..., 18)` and strict bool decoding
-
-Storage parser contract:
-- volumes from 8-column merged volume TSV
-- overlays synthesized from 4-column cell TSV (`name,manifest,running,root`)
-
-Operational behavior:
-- prefers long-lived IPC session
-- on transport failure marks bridge disconnected and surfaces reconnect UI
-
-
-10. Developer guardrails
-------------------------
-- Keep `cellctl -T` schema validation strict and fail-closed.
-- Keep exported field names lowercase `snake_case` and stable.
-- Preserve human-table default for read commands.
-- Keep machine output contracts stable (`-T`, headers, field order with `-o`).
-- Preserve confirmation gates for destructive paths (`--all`, `--orphans`, restore/delete).
-- Maintain name and mount-spec validators as single sources of truth.
