-NetBSD cells-v2 operations guide (unified `cellmgr`)
-====================================================
-
-Status
-------
-This guide documents operational workflows for the current implementation.
-
-Primary references:
-- `usr.sbin/cellmgr/cellmgr.8`
-- `usr.sbin/cellctl/cellctl.8`
-- `usr.sbin/cellui/cellui.8`
-- `doc/specs/netbsd-cells-specification.txt`
-
-
-1. Day-0 bootstrap and first converge
--------------------------------------
-Recommended bootstrap path:
-
-1) Initialize host integration and base layer:
-   - `cellmgr system bootstrap`
-2) Create desired manifests:
-   - `cellmgr volume create data --scope desired`
-   - `cellmgr cell create app --cmd '/usr/sbin/daemon-example' --scope desired`
-3) Review planned drift:
-   - `cellmgr apply --dry-run --all`
-4) Converge:
-   - `cellmgr apply --all`
-
-What bootstrap does:
-- ensures `cellmgr=YES` in `/etc/rc.conf`
-- ensures `secmodel_cell` is loaded and persistent via `/etc/modules.conf`
-- writes default `/etc/cellmgr.conf` when absent
-- fetches release sets and builds the shared base layer
-- writable runtime paths `/etc`, `/var`, `/tmp`, `/home`, `/root`, `/usr/pkg`, and `/opt`
-  resolve via per-cell `/.overlay`
-
-
-2. Read workflows (day-1/day-2)
--------------------------------
-Primary read commands:
-- `cellmgr cell list|show|fields`
-- `cellmgr volume list|show|fields`
-
-Projection controls:
-- `--view merged|desired|runtime`
-- `-o field1,field2,...`
-- `-T` for TSV, `-H` for headerless TSV
-
-Examples:
-- `cellmgr cell list --view merged`
-- `cellmgr cell list --view runtime -T -H -o name,cid,procs,cpu1s,cpu10s,age`
-- `cellmgr volume list --view merged -T -o name,manifest,runtime,mounted,refs,used_by`
-
-Output reminders:
-- `age` is raw seconds in TSV and humanized in table mode
-- boolean-like fields are `1|0` in TSV and `YES|NO` in table mode
-
-
-3. Mutation workflows and scope intent
---------------------------------------
-Scope guidance:
-- use `--scope desired` for GitOps/declarative-only changes
-- use `--scope runtime` for immediate live actions
-- use `--scope both` when intent must be reflected immediately and declaratively
-
-Command families:
-- `cell create|set`: `--scope desired|both`
-- `cell start|stop|restart`: `--scope runtime|both`
-- `cell remove`: `--scope desired|runtime|both`
-- `volume create|set`: `--scope desired|both`
-- `volume remove`: `--scope desired|runtime|both`
-
-Useful examples:
-- `cellmgr cell set api --autostart YES --scope desired`
-- `cellmgr cell start api --scope runtime`
-- `cellmgr cell stop api --scope both` (also sets desired autostart to `NO`)
-- `cellmgr volume create uploads -m 0750 --scope both`
-
-
-4. Reconciliation runbook (`cellmgr apply`)
--------------------------------------------
-Canonical command:
-- `cellmgr apply [--all|<name>...] [--dry-run] [--reapply] [--restart-changed] [--silent|-v]`
-
-Operational sequence:
-
-    desired manifests
-          |
-          v
-    dependency order
-          |
-          v
-    reconcile volumes
-          |
-          v
-    reconcile cells
-      |   |    |
-      |   |    +--> optional apply plan
-      |   +--------> optional restart
-      +------------> optional healthcheck
-
-Options:
-- `--dry-run`: print plan, return exit code `2` when changes would be needed
-- `--reapply`: re-run apply plan even when plan hash is unchanged
-- `--restart-changed`: restart on policy drift (`profile/ports/rlimits`)
-- `--silent` and `-v` are mutually exclusive
-
-Recommended production flow:
-1) `cellmgr apply --dry-run --all`
-2) review planned `CREATE/UPDATE/START/STOP/APPLY/HEALTHCHECK` actions
-3) `cellmgr apply --all`
-
-
-5. Declarative apply plans (`*.apply`)
---------------------------------------
-Supported directives:
-- `PKG`, `EXEC`, `DIR`, `LINE`, `SYMLINK`, `COPY`, `UNTAR`, `FILE_BEGIN...FILE_END`, `PATCH_BEGIN...PATCH_END`
-
-Rules that matter operationally:
-- directives must be uppercase
-- `FILE_BEGIN` and `PATCH_BEGIN` targets must be absolute paths
-- `UNTAR` target must be absolute
-- `COPY` and `UNTAR` host sources can be absolute or relative to the plan location
-- `COPY` and `UNTAR` source content contributes to apply hashing (changes auto-trigger apply)
-- for stopped (`autostart=NO`) cells, plan execution is ephemeral (start/apply/stop)
-
-Manual run for one cell:
-- `cellmgr cell plan run <name>`
-- `cellmgr cell plan run <name> --file /path/to/custom.apply`
-- `cellmgr cell plan run <name> --ephemeral`
-
-
-6. Backup and restore operations
---------------------------------
-Volume backups:
-- create: `cellmgr volume backup create <name>`
-- list: `cellmgr volume backup list <name> [-T] [-H]`
-- restore: `cellmgr volume backup restore <name> --latest [--manifest] --yes`
-- delete: `cellmgr volume backup delete <name> --latest --yes`
-
-Overlay backups (per cell runtime overlay):
-- create: `cellmgr cell backup create <name>`
-- list: `cellmgr cell backup list <name> [-T] [-H]`
-- restore: `cellmgr cell backup restore <name> --latest [--manifest] --yes`
-- delete: `cellmgr cell backup delete <name> --latest --yes`
-
-Important constraints:
-- volume restore/delete is blocked while volume is mounted
-- overlay backup/restore is blocked while cell is running or overlay is mounted
-- restore/delete require confirmation (or `--yes`)
-
-
-7. Reset and cleanup workflows
-------------------------------
-Targeted destructive reset:
-- `cellmgr system reset [--scope desired|runtime|both] [--cells] [--volumes] [--yes]`
-
-Behavior:
-- if neither `--cells` nor `--volumes` is given, both are reset
-- internally chains destructive `remove --all` operations
-
-Orphan cleanup examples:
-- `cellmgr cell remove --orphans --scope runtime --yes`
-- `cellmgr volume remove --orphans --scope runtime --yes`
-
-
-8. Safety model and non-interactive automation
-----------------------------------------------
-Destructive operations are guarded:
-- `--all` / `--orphans` removals
-- backup restore/delete actions
-
-Automation guidance:
-- always pass `--yes` for non-interactive jobs
-- treat apply exit code `2` as drift (not as fatal failure)
-- keep TSV contracts pinned (`-T`, explicit `-o`, explicit `--view`)
-
-Validation highlights:
-- names must match `[A-Za-z0-9._-]`
-- mount specs must be `<volume>:<absolute-target>[:ro|rw]`
-
-
-9. Incident triage order
-------------------------
-1) `cellmgr cell list --view merged`
-2) `cellmgr apply --dry-run --all`
-3) `cellctl list -T` and `cellctl stats -T`
-4) host syslog (supervise output/restarts)
-5) `cellmgr cell shell <name>` for in-cell inspection
-6) if config drift suspected, inspect:
-   - `/etc/cellmgr/<name>.cell`
-   - `/var/cellmgr/cells/<name>/cell.conf`
-
-
-10. `cellui` operational notes
-------------------------------
-`cellui` behavior:
-- refreshes every 4 seconds
-- uses persistent `cellmgr ipc serve --stdio` bridge when available
-- has two modes: cell management and storage management (`TAB`)
-- supports backup create/restore/delete from storage mode
-
-Failure behavior:
-- command/schema failures are surfaced as refresh errors
-- malformed TSV lines are currently skipped by the parser
-- IPC disconnect triggers reconnect dialog (`Enter` to reconnect)
